name: Huguenots
description: In the years leading up to and particularly after the Revocation of the Edict of Nantes (1685), many French Protestants moved to London, particularly in the West End and Spitalfields area.

name: English Diplomats
description: Individuals "warranted by [their] sovereign to represent, officially, the English government to a foreign power or interest, located outside of English territorial boundaries" (Bell, Handlist, 3)

name: St Pauls School London
description: Teachers and pupils of St Pauls School London

name: Republicans
description:
Those holding "a faith in the power of institutions to circumscribe
the authority of the monarch, allied to a belief that such institutions -
Parliament, the law courts, local and national government  - had the
means to make individuals more virtuous and so better able to govern."  (Andrew Hadfield, "Republicanism in Sixteenth- and
Seventeenth-Century Britain")

name: Virginia Company
description: a joint stock company chartered to establish colonies in North America

name: Fraternity of Sireniacal Gentlemen
description: A drinking society of some of the Elizabethan era's leading literary figures. They met on the first Friday of every month at the Mermaid, Three Cranes, or Mitre taverns in London.

name: Earl of Essex's army
description: The parliamentarian army commanded by the third Earl of Essex in the first English Civil War

name: Privy Councillors
description: Members of formal body of advisors to the sovereign

name: Dublin Philosophical Society
description: A society "agreeable to the design of the Royal Society in London" which grew out of a group headed by William Molyneux who were collecting materials for the projected Pitt atlas of the British Isles. Formed in January 1684, hiatus 1688, revived 1694 with meetings ceasing by 1698. The Society was refounded by Samuel Molyneux in 1707, but lasted for only one year.

name: Jesuits
description: members of the Society of Jesus

name: The King's Musik
description: Members of the British Monarch's Music, musicians employed at the English Court. (Members of court chapels were organized separately, though some members of the King's Musik were also  chapel members.)

name: Trustees of Blackfriars Playhouse
description: Legal trustees of the (Second) Blackfriars Theatre

name: Recipe Contributors for Sir Kenelm Digby's Closet Opened

description: A major branch of Protestantism that follows the theological tradition and forms of Christian practice of John Calvin

name: Royal Society
description: society for the encouragement of philosophical studies

name: Patrons of the Mermaid Tavern
description: Patrons of the Mermaid tavern;  a broader category than the separate group, "Fraternity of Sireniacal gentlemen"

name: Opera of the Nobility
description: The Opera of the Nobility was an opera company set up and funded in 1733 by a group of nobles (under Frederick, Prince of Wales) opposed to George II of England, in order to rival the Royal Academy of Music company under Handel, who was backed by George II and his queen).

name: Postmasters
description: Administrators placed in charge of the Royal Post or associated systems

name: Royal Academy of Music I and II
description: The Royal Academy of Music was a company founded in February 1719, during George Frideric Handel's residence at Cannons, by a group of aristocrats to secure themselves a constant supply of baroque (Italian) opera. The first Academy lasted until 1728, but Handel immediately started a second Academy.

name: Members of the College of Physicians
description: The College of Physicians was founded to regulate medical practice in early modern London. (It came to be known as the 'Royal College of Physicians' later in the 17th century.) The first president, Linacre, wanted to found an academic body for physicians rather than a trade guild of the kind which regulated surgeons and apothecaries. A degree was usually required to gain a license. Candidates took an oral examination to demonstrate that they were classically educated and had sufficient medical knowledge.

name: Colonial America
description: British American colonists and their relations

name: New Model Army
description: Main army of the Long Parliament, Commonwealth and Protectorate

name: Ejected Ministers
description: ministers ejected from the Church of England for nonconformity following 1662 Act of Uniformity

name: Saddlers and harness makers
description: People working as saddlers or harness makers, or members of guilds or companies governing these trades

name: Hebraists
description: specialists in Jewish, Hebrew and Hebraic studies

name: Benefactors of the Bodleian Library
description: People who donated money, books, and MSS to the University of Oxford's Bodleian Library on its refoundation in 1600

name: Translators of the King James Bible

name: Gray's Inn

name: Lincoln's Inn
